The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series, Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in the U.S.), at literary festivals and bookstores. They had every good reason to celebrate.
Since his first appearance on June 26, 1997, this "Boy Who Lived" has become a "symbol of resilience and perseverance."
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, been translated into more than 70 languages, and has cumulatively sold 450 million copies.
Eight films based on this book have earned a cumulative $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
It is hard for people of a certain age and those with a literary mindset to imagine a day when global audiences are no longer captivated by Rowling's works.
Therefore, I am still amazed every time I recall the poor reception my students gave to "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" in the fall of 1999, when I included the book in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching a series of courses on "Bestselling American Books" since 1993.
This course examines popular works from the 17th century up to the present, inviting students to consider why and in what ways these best-selling works have attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I have students choose a final work that represents popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, Hurricane Floyd fiercely struck the American coast.
In June, the American publisher of the series urgently released the hardcover edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets," to bookstores.
The institution also published the third book in the series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," on September 8, as well as a paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone."
By the end of the month, Rowling's novels had occupied the top three positions on The New York Times bestseller list, while the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" had topped the paperback books sales chart.
Time magazine even featured this glasses-wearing wizard on its cover.
The image of Harry Potter is everywhere in sight.
My students are eager to know why such enthusiasm exists.
Goodness, they are utterly disappointed.
In their view, the Harry Potter series is merely second-rate nonsense, far inferior to cherished works such as The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings, which hold a special place in their childhood memories.
Although their childhood had just ended a few years ago, they criticized "Harry Potter" just like many notorious adult critics, calling it "fabricated," "poorly written," "clichéd," and "boring."
Sure, please provide the sentence you'd like translated from Chinese to English.
In their eyes, Harry had neither miracles, nor wit, nor warmth.
I was surprised by the students' resentment, but in hindsight, there was nothing really to be surprised about.
Although adults have always constituted a significant portion of the Harry Potter audience, these students happen to be in the exact age group that is unable to objectively comprehend the phenomenon of Harry Potter.
They were past the age of reading children's books, yet too young to have their own children (at that time I had just had my own child), and they eagerly insisted that although the Harry Potter series was now very popular, it would soon be forgotten.
In the fall of the following year, that is, 2000, the next group of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" as their final analysis assignment, just like their predecessors, confidently rejecting the book.
Let's fast-forward to spring 2007.
After putting the course on hold for a few years, I taught "Bestsellers in America" again.
When students chose a final analysis work, they selected "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone."
And I am ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
These are a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first read Rowling's works not as university students but as teenagers, just beginning their adolescence. This means they grew up alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione, becoming young adults together.
The same thing happened again in the fall of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto rather than a label.
Could Harry disappear from memory?
It's impossible as long as we are still alive.
Since 2010, I have taught the popular book course twice, and both times the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final review.
Are you tired of Potter?
Based on the reviews from the Harry Potter series in another course I teach on children's literature, this seems unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the curriculum, but instead of selecting "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone," I chose "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban"—this is my favorite among the seven Harry Potter novels. It marks the transition of the series from children's literature to young adult fiction, and it offers complex portrayals of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also like this book the most.
But how long will the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Each time I teach a course in children's literature, I first conduct a poll: "Which books on the syllabus did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban."
In 2012, this figure rose to 94%.
But in the following years, the percentage continued to decline —— it was 87% in 2014, and dropped to 81% in 2016.
None of these are science, I know.
But I'm curious: next spring, when I teach "Children's Literature" again, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that the status of Harry Potter is constantly declining and will never become a timeless classic?
Is there still a balance point ahead where the percentage can remain stable and stop decreasing?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Up until then, I was glad to have invited him into my classroom all along.
